Honestly, E. Without taking a poll or tapping into the political pulse of the nation with a talk show of my very own, I think the average American doesn't care about the pledge either way. It can stay up or it can go down. More are concerned about getting by, an illness in the family, a personal circumstance more intimate than two words and the history thereof as they go on with their lives. Not everyone takes the day's topic to heart and it's all right as long as they choose to let it go by instead of avoid every topic that comes along. It's setting your priorities, and shrugging your shoulders doesn't make one a dull person because a reference to a higher being in schools fails to raise bile in one's throat. Do you think perhaps few feel inclined to involve themselves, as you surmise, because the issue is important to a minority and has less to do with Bush's simple reaction?<br>
