<br>
Don't mix up the Pilgrims with the Puritans, there are political and religious differences between them and their beliefs in how their objectives should be attained.  Pilgrims believed they should separate themselves from England if they did not follow what they percieved as God's will.  Puritans believed that the British government and church should be purified of secular elements. (To reinforce the concept of the divine right of the monarchy to rule.)  The last time I checked, the Massachusetts Bay Colony and Plymouth were not located in Rhode Island, but Massachusetts.  Did history rewrite itself since my days in school or did the state borders shift that much?  Pennsylvania, New Amsterdam (now New York), Rhode Island, Connecticut, Delaware, and Virginia also had early settlements established by people seeking to practice religion in their own way.  Whether or not their descendants later became intolerant of different faiths and forgot why their forefathers came there in the first place does not change the fact that they were established for religious reasons.<br>
<br>
As far as settlements like Fort Amsterdam and Jamestown setting up provisions for making money via trade with Europe, what horrible self-serving people they must have been for taking steps to ensure they and their families can eat and survive to see the next year.  As opposed to expecting the Native Americans who already live in the region to give them everything they need.  So what if a European business or bank that spent their money to fund these colonists' trip here and initial costs to establish a colony or trade center finally turned them a profit after a decade or so?  They saw an opportunity to make money from someone seeking to leave for unexplored country, took enormous financial risks and it eventually paid off.  <br>
<br>
And  &quot;The people did not flee england becuase of religous persecution, they can over here to be separate from the religion of the day.&quot;<br>
<br>
Are you saying that from 1553 to 1558, Mary Tudor did not order the arrest and execution of hundreds of people of the Protestant faith in order to return England to the Roman Catholic faith?  This wholesale slaughter, which earned her the nickname &quot;Bloody Mary&quot; led to an exodus of many not of the Catholic faith from England to other parts of Europe and America.  Revisionist history strikes again. <br>
<br>
Gurunt states:  &quot;This lawsuit and the fact that Americans will actually argue about this retarded thing with such ferver is why people in other countries who starve for a living think Americans are pampered self-centered assholes.&quot;<br>
<br>
I really don't care overmuch what other countries think of us, as they hate us anyway.  People in other countries starve due to their own government's abuses of powers and &quot;retarded things&quot; like worrying about what the United States is doing, instead of the fact that their own people are experiencing drought, famine, epidemic illnesses and what they can do to curtail their own problems.<br>
<br>
Varro states:  &quot;My point with the book issue is not that I doubt the possibility of books being banned, but that I believe that issue is seperate from the one we are talking about. It is a what if claim that really has no basis in this argument because the reasons for banning a book are quite different from the reasons for removing &quot;Under God&quot; from the pledge.&quot;<br>
<br>
