&quot;If you are trying to convince people that your point of view is valid and that you really are ok with other people's belief systems - labeling all athiests and others who don'g agree with you wont win you many converts.&quot;<br>
<br>
Your assumptions have become impressive in their breadth and lack of connection to any shred of reality. <br>
<br>
1) I am not trying to convince anyone of anything in this thread. I am arguing a point or three. There is a difference. <br>
<br>
2) I am not trying to gain converts. See point #1<br>
<br>
3) I am generally okay with other's belief systems and have not said otherwise. I challenge anyone to show me where I have denigrated a belief system. I may denigrate an indivdual believer, an establishment dedicated to a belief system, or the trappings thereof, but I rarely deride a belief system in itself. Again, there is a difference.<br>
<br>
4) What, precisely, did I label the atheists and the media?<br>
<br>
5) What bearing does the above quote have on anything. I'd say &quot;unfocused&quot; again, but I believe I've used it enough.<br>
<br>
&quot;While I myself am a christian and believe in god - I don't believe forcing other people to say the words 'under god', have prayers in school or the rest of the pledge and trying to brainwash little kids is a good choice - I suppose that is where we are different.&quot;<br>
<br>
Good for you. I'm not Christian, and don't profess any sort of faith or belief in anything, much to my disappointment. I have also stated early on in this argument that the 9th Circuit Court made the right call. Did you read some part of my post that I didn't? I never said a single thing about the &quot;under God&quot; line in reference to your post. <br>
<br>
Reciting a Pledge and brainwashing are a bit different. If you cannot see this statement as true, try researching MK-ULTRA, the USSR under Stalin, Chairman Mao, Orwell's 1984, or Psycholinguistics practiced by Revivalist ministers. Reciting a Pledge once a day is socialization and might just help in building good citizens.<br>
<br>
The best part about this is the last line. I gave a better argument as to why the 9th Circuit was correct far earlier in the discussion, and I am somehow on the side of the &quot;under God&quot; crowd.<br>
<br>
Imaginative. <br>
