<br>
The comparison here is that, by having the phrase &quot;under God&quot; in the Pledge and having govt schools ask children to recite the Pledge, we are tacitly forcing the child to express implicitly some level of belief in the existence of some God. <br>
<br>
When you use money however, you are handing off an item that merely has an implicit belief in God emblazoned upon it, and this does not constitute a statement on your part. You did not, after all, write those words, and do not necessairly intend the transfer of cash as some sort of odd proseltyzing.<br>
<br>
I'm not terribly conversant on the logic used in that decision and am merely attempting to relate the gist of it from memory. Please don't consider this a statement of my position on the &quot;In God we trust&quot; line. <p>a_Bearhat01<BR>
